    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Last time I went to the Philippines I really wanted to go to the famous
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apo_Reef">Apo Reef</a>, but my stinginess actually
kept me from going there. This time though I was really determined to get my
ass over there. It&rsquo;s a little bit tricky to get to
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apo_Reef">Apo Reef</a>, but trust me, it&rsquo;s
definitely worth the effort.</p>

<!-- more -->


<p>Now, the tricky part is actually to find a way to get to the reef itself. Since
it&rsquo;s located south-east of the island
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mindoro">Mindoro</a> not to many dive shops operate
the reef, nor is there a quick easy way to get to any of the shops that do.
You basically have two options, either you go with a dive shop in Coron, or you
go by one located on Mindoro. I definitely recommend
<a href="http://www.aporeefclub.com/">Apo Reef Club</a> located about one hour
south of <a href="https://goo.gl/maps/7SqZ94urZDF2">Sablayan</a> on
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mindoro">Mindoro</a>.
<a href="http://www.aporeefclub.com/">Apo Reef Club</a> is a professional
dive shop run by Micheal Roos and has been doing trips to
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apo_Reef">Apo Reef</a> for about eight years now.</p>

<p>The easiest way to get to <a href="http://www.aporeefclub.com/">Apo Reef Club</a> is to
take a flight from Manila to <a href="https://goo.gl/maps/TNo6gVdZofM2">San Jose</a> and
then ask <a href="http://www.aporeefclub.com/">Apo Reef Club</a> for a pickup in
<a href="https://goo.gl/maps/TNo6gVdZofM2">San Jose</a>. The flight from Manila departs
roughly three times a week, so be sure to make your
booking in time. However, if you feel a little bit more adventures you can take
the one of the buses from Manila down to Batangas and from there try to find
your own way over to Mindoro and down to
<a href="https://goo.gl/maps/TNo6gVdZofM2">San Jose</a>. Or, you could take the famous
<a href="https://www.facebook.com/Dimple-Star-Transport-10150148192685221/">Dimplestar Bus</a>
which will take you all the way. I chose the latter and went with the
<a href="https://www.facebook.com/Dimple-Star-Transport-10150148192685221/">Dimplestar</a>
all the way from Manila to <a href="http://www.aporeefclub.com/">Apo Reef Club</a> (the
bus line is actually going all the way to
<a href="https://goo.gl/maps/TNo6gVdZofM2">San Jose</a>, but
<a href="http://www.aporeefclub.com/">Apo Reef Club</a> is located north of
<a href="https://goo.gl/maps/TNo6gVdZofM2">San Jose</a>, so
you&rsquo;ll have to get off in a small &ldquo;town&rdquo; called Concepcion, where
<a href="http://www.aporeefclub.com/">Apo Reef Club</a> will pick you up). <strong>Note</strong>, you&rsquo;ll
also have to tell
<a href="https://www.facebook.com/Dimple-Star-Transport-10150148192685221/">Dimplestar</a>
that you are going either to <a href="http://www.aporeefclub.com/">Apo Reef Club</a> or to
<a href="https://goo.gl/maps/7SqZ94urZDF2">Sablayan</a>. It&rsquo;s probably safer to say
<a href="https://goo.gl/maps/7SqZ94urZDF2">Sablayan</a>, because they might not know
<a href="http://www.aporeefclub.com/">Apo Reef Club</a>. The reason you have to mention
this is because there is two ways to <a href="https://goo.gl/maps/TNo6gVdZofM2">San Jose</a>,
one is passing <a href="https://goo.gl/maps/7SqZ94urZDF2">Sablayan</a> and
<a href="http://www.aporeefclub.com/">Apo Reef Club</a>, the other one is not (it&rsquo;s taking
the east route of Mindoro, and you don&rsquo;t want to get stuck in
<a href="https://goo.gl/maps/TNo6gVdZofM2">San Jose</a>).</p>

<p>With that being said, prepare yourself for a 13 hour long bus ride, including
several hundred stops, a delayed and very slow ferry, the bumpiest road you&rsquo;ll
ever experience and some extremely loud fucking techno music. If thats what you
fancy and you&rsquo;ve only got 800 php to spend on the ride, this is the way to go.
Otherwise, just take the god damn flight to
 <a href="https://goo.gl/maps/TNo6gVdZofM2">San Jose</a> - I&rsquo;m for sure not doing
that nightmare bus ride ever again. And yes, there is some sort of schedule with
these buses, but as everything else in the Philippines it may vary from day to
day so you better call them and ask first. Oh, the phone numbers doesn&rsquo;t really
work either so you better get your ass to the bus station and ask the guy behind
the counter; welcome to the Philippines ;)</p>

<p>Enough ranting on how to get there, here&rsquo;s the goodies about
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apo_Reef">Apo Reef</a>.
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apo_Reef">Apo Reef</a> is the world&rsquo;s second-largest
contiguous coral reef system and the largest in the Philippines. It houses 385
species of colorful marine fishes including families of sharks (including
hammerheads if it&rsquo;s the right season), stingrays,
mantas (seasonal), school of jacks, snappers, barracudas, mackerels,
and green humphead parrotfish, swarms of tropical aquarium fish, blennies
and gobies. The visibility is above anything I&rsquo;ve ever seen before.
I did eleven dives at the reef and we had 40m+ visibility on every dive
(if you aren&rsquo;t a diver, you can literally just snorkel - visibility is that
good). The thing that really blew me away (except the stuff mentioned above) was
that the reef wasn&rsquo;t crowded with divers, not a single one actually, it&rsquo;s only
you, your buddies and the fishes - it&rsquo;s extremely cool.</p>

<p>Here&rsquo;s a quote from me describing it on facebook,
&ldquo;<em>Imagine a pool (you know, where you have a visibility of 40m+).</em>
<em>And then you add every freaking colorful fish you can think of.</em>
<em>And then throw in some sharks, some mackerel, some humpheads, some barracudas,</em>
<em>and yeah throw in some turtles while you&rsquo;re at it. Of course don&rsquo;t forget about</em>
<em>the incredible beautiful scenery (big walls etc).</em>
<em>Then you multiply that imagination by a hundred and maybe, only maybe, you come</em>
<em>close to apo reef.</em>
<em>So, yes, even if the thirteen hour ride here was one of the worst ever,</em>
<em>it was worth it.</em>
<strong>That school of humpheads is just the craziest shit I ever seen.</strong>&rdquo;</p>

<p>Apo Reef is simply stunning and definitely one of my favourite dive sites.</p>

