    <title type="html"><![CDATA[Malapascua - Paradise Island With the Thresher Sharks]]></title>
    <link href="http://www.ensamiasien.se//blog/2015/10/25/malapascua-paradise-island-with-the-thresher-sharks/"/>
    <updated>2015-10-25T08:17:13+01:00</updated>
    <id>http://www.ensamiasien.se//blog/2015/10/25/malapascua-paradise-island-with-the-thresher-sharks</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Malapascua is the name of an island north of Cebu in the Central Visayas region
in the Philippines. It&rsquo;s a quite small island mostly known for its diving and
the &ldquo;guarantee&rdquo; of seeing the famous thresher sharks. Malapascua is definitely
worth a visit and it&rsquo;s actually <strong>not</strong> that tricky to get there, its just like
everything else in the Philippines; <strong>you&rsquo;ve got to have patiense and a lot of
time</strong></p>

<!-- more -->


<p>Easiest way to get in is to take a flight (depending on where you comning from
that is) to Cebu city and then arrange for a private ride (van/taxi) to a city
called Maya. This is of course the most expensive option, the private ride will
probably set you back around 1800 - 2500 php depending on your bargaining skills
, but with that being said, it&rsquo;s also definitely the fastest option. The cheaper
alternative is to go to the &ldquo;north bus station&rdquo; in Cebu city and take the local
bus that leaves about four times per day. That ride will only cost you around
160 php, but could be quite long (mine took almost six hours) so be sure to
bring entertainment.</p>

<p>No matter which alternative you choose, you will end up at the port in Maya
city. From there it&rsquo;s only a short boat ride (about 20 minutes) until you reach
Malapascua island. Transfer boats leave regularly (between 6am - 6pm) and cost
80 php. If the tide is low, you will have to pay for a small &ldquo;transfer boat&rdquo;
which will cost you 20 php (this is 20 php on the Maya side, and another 20 php
at the Malapascua side). They will try to make you pay a lot more, but just ask
the locals how much they pay and tell the boat man that you want the same price
as them.</p>

<p>When you&rsquo;re finally on the actual island you will have tons of resorts, dive
centers and cheap bungalow accommodations. I went for a private bungalow, right
on the beach next to my diving center for only 700 php per night. My stay was
during the &ldquo;low season&rdquo; though so be prepared to pay up to 1200 for these
bungalows (the place I stayed at was called &ldquo;Dannio&rsquo;s&rdquo; or something similar, I
had hard time with that name). As for the diving I went with a place called
Evolution, a very professional shop located at the end of the beach. There are
tons of options so I recommend just walking around and grab the one you&rsquo;re most
comfortable with. If you do two dives in one day that will cost you somewhere
around 2600 php and upwards, depending on your choosing.</p>

<p>I had a great stay at Evolution and made a lot of new friends. Evolution really
takes care of you and makes you feel at home. They are running a very
professional dive shop, with good dive masters, good equipment and good
briefings, everything is simply top notch. Diving with the thresher sharks is
simply stunning and definitely the main attraction, however make sure not to
miss all the macro stuff.</p>

<p>Mustafa, Seden, Carlo and Freedom, you will always have room in my hostel heart.
Until next time, Mustafa and Carlo, make sure to take good care of your better
halves ;)</p>

